{"id":"1907.03906","submitter":"Ignacio Rozada","authors":"Ignacio Rozada, Maliheh Aramon, Jonathan Machta, Helmut G. Katzgraber","title":"Effects of setting the temperatures in the parallel tempering Monte\n  Carlo algorithm","comments":"10 pages, 27 figures, 1 table","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 100, 043311 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.100.043311","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.comp-ph cond-mat.stat-mech math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Parallel tempering Monte Carlo has proven to be an efficient method in\noptimization and sampling applications. Having an optimized temperature set\nenhances the efficiency of the algorithm through more-frequent replica visits\nto the temperature limits. The approaches for finding an optimal temperature\nset can be divided into two main categories. The methods of the first category\ndistribute the replicas such that the swapping ratio between neighbouring\nreplicas is constant and independent of the temperature values. The\nsecond-category techniques including the feedback-optimized method, on the\nother hand, aim for a temperature distribution that has higher density at\nsimulation bottlenecks, resulting in temperature-dependent replica-exchange\nprobabilities. In this paper, we compare the performance of various temperature\nsetting methods on both sparse and fully-connected spin-glass problems as well\nas fully-connected Wishart problems that have planted solutions. These include\ntwo classes of problems that have either continuous or discontinuous phase\ntransitions in the order parameter. Our results demonstrate that there is no\nperformance advantage for the methods that promote nonuniform swapping\nprobabilities on spin-glass problems where the order parameter has a smooth\ntransition between phases at the critical temperature. However, on Wishart\nproblems that have a first-order phase transition at low temperatures, the\nfeedback-optimized method exhibits a time-to-solution speedup of at least a\nfactor of two over the other approaches.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Jul 2019 23:20:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 8 Nov 2019 18:24:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-11"}
